description.text: At least 15 people killed, 34 injured, 4 missing, more than 16,646 displaced and 1,069 houses destroyed and 1,791 damaged from the earthquake and tsunami in Coquimbo, Valparaiso and Region Metropolitana. A landslide occurred at Canela. One person died of a heart attack while running out of a building at Beccar, Argentina. Felt (IX) at Illapel; (VIII) at Coquimbo, La Serena and Ovalle; (VII) at Andacollo, El Quisco, La Calera, La Ligua, Los Andes, Los Vilos, Rancagua, San Antonio, Santiago and Tiltil. Felt widely from Arica to Valdivia. Felt (VI) at San Juan; (V) at La Rioja and San Martin; (IV) at Cordoba, Mendoza and San Rafael, Argentina. Felt (II) at Sao Paulo, Brazil and at Asuncion, Paraguay. Felt at Lima, Peru and at Montevideo and Punta del Este, Uruguay. A Pacific-wide tsunami was generated with maximum wave amplitudes in meters recorded at the following selected tide stations: 4.75 at Coquimbo, 1.86 at Quintero, 1.78 at Valparaiso, 1.28 at Talcahuano, 1.21 on Juan Fernandez Islands, 1.14 at Caldera, 1.09 at Chanaral, 1.04 at San Antonio, 0.88 at Constitucion, 0.83 on Easter Island, 0.77 at Huasco, 0.58 at Arica and 0.52 at Antofagasta, Chile; 0.67 at Pago Pago, American Samoa; 0.15 at Quepos, Costa Rica; 0.56 on Isla Santa Cruz, Ecuador; 1.37 on Nuku Hiva, French Polynesia; 0.26 at Kushimoto, Japan; 0.37 at Puerto Angel, Mexico; 0.16 at Ouinne, New Caledonia; 0.35 on Chatham Islands, New Zealand; 0.55 at La Punta, Peru; 0.20 at Apia, Samoa; 0.09 at Nuku`alofa, Tonga; 0.27 at King Cove, Alaska, USA; 0.34 at Ventura, California; 0.90 at Hilo, Hawaii; 0.21 on Efate, Vanuatu.

48 km (29 miles) W of Illapel, Chile (pop 22816) 69 km (42 miles) WNW of Salamanca, Chile (pop 13265) 106 km (65 miles) NNW of La Ligua, Chile (pop 24857) 116 km (72 miles) SSW of Ovalle, Chile (pop 77138) 230 km (142 miles) NNW of Santiago, Chile (pop 4837295)
